</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA051489-0010 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 56612 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
May 14, 1989, Sunday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Book Review; Page 9; Book Review Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
776 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
'THREE AND FOUR AND GLORIA!'; 
</P>
<P>
SETTLING THE SCORE BY MICHAEL LEVIN (SIMON &amp; SCHUSTER: $17.95; 239 PP.; 
0-671-66761-0) 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Mark Swed, Swed is classical music critic for 7 Days in New York. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Classical music is a business like no other. To become a performer, 
particularly an instrumentalist, requires first the sacrifice of youth -- a 
virtuoso must begin young, the younger the better, and then submerge childhood 
in dulling, daily hours of practice. 
</P>
<P>
Next comes the cutthroat competition. This happens at all stages of career 
building and career maintaining -- competing to get into the best conservatory, 
competing to get the best teacher, competing to get into the prestigious 
competitions so you can compete some more, competing for management, and then 
auditioning, auditioning and more auditioning. 
</P>
<P>
What are the rewards? Well, you can make a lot of money and become a celebrity, 
so that you can live the life of a Gypsy in airports, faceless hotels, concert 
halls and sterile recording studios. Or if you manage to land a coveted spot in 
a major orchestra, you can spend your life playing what the conductor tells you 
to play, the way he wants you to play it, all the while seething while someone 
else plays the Tchaikovsky concerto. 
</P>
<P>
Singers, conductors, composers, management types don't have to start quite so 
early, but usually they come out of the pool of musicians who do, and each of 
those areas of the classical music business has its hazards as well. Remember, 
there was a time when young boys underwent castration for their careers' sake. 
</P>
<P>
So, it is hardly surprising that musicians are sometimes eccentric, petty, 
immature or just plain nutty. And a very funny behind-the-classical-music-scene 
roman a clef could be written about the world. 
</P>
<P>
"Settling the Score," unfortunately, is not that book, as hard as it tries to 
be. 
</P>
<P>
Michael Levin's targets are conductors, orchestra members, singers, composers 
(Levin's sniveling descriptions of new music are appallingly foul-mouthed), 
managers, despicable music teachers, wives and lovers and mistresses of all of 
the above, stage-door guards. Have I left anyone out? Oh, yes, and Mozart. 
</P>
<P>
The premise of the novel is that the director of a New York chorus discovers a 
lost Mass by Mozart, which is about to have its premiere in Carnegie Hall. 
Mozart had supposedly written the Mass as a display piece for a lady oboist 
after whom he lusted. When she rejected his advances, the composer evidently 
withdrew his music. 
</P>
<P>
No one knows that Donald, our chorus director, is a great conductor because he 
suffers from stage fright, so the world premiere of the Mass is offered to a 
dashing conductor of something called the Royal Symphonic, a former college 
wrestler who happens to be a barely literate nincompoop married to the daughter 
of the Royal Symphonic's principal donor. 
</P>
<P>
Andrew, the conductor, seems principally interested in pretty women in the 
orchestra -- his wife is a frigid, ambitious dragon lady. He also is a 
political naif, as well as a musical one, and he has managed to enrage both the 
Palestinians and the Jews. And so the stage is set for the gala Mozart premiere 
and his American debut, a media event during which everything that can go wrong 
does. You can find out for yourself how he winds up on the podium and on 
national television wearing a torn mint-green tuxedo and sneakers. 
</P>
<P>
To parody the classical music world, however, one has to know it better than 
Levin appears to. From the first page, the novel demonstrates a very shaky 
grasp of music, of how it is made. For instance, Donald, the chorus master, 
asks, at the opening of the book, for his singers to begin two measures before 
the "Gloria" and then calls out, "Three and four and Gloria!" -- Levin thus 
confusing those two beats with two bars. A small detail, perhaps, not one that 
inspires confidence. 
</P>
<P>
Moreover, Levin seems to have only the vaguest notions how an orchestra 
administration works -- the music director of the New York Philharmonic, or its 
"Settling the Score" equivalent, does not hire a chorus master; the general 
manager does not leave it up to his assistant to negotiate the fees of 
celebrated guest conductors, and on and on. 
</P>
<P>
Certainly in a work of fiction and especially a parody, the author is free to 
invent however he likes for the sake of a laugh or to help the plot along. But 
Levin banks heavily on the intrigue of insider information -- the appeal of his 
previous novel, "The Socratic Method," was its behind-the-scenes look at Ivy 
League law school, something Levin, a law graduate, knows something about. 
</P>
<P>
Not so here. "Settling the Score," besides being inelegantly written, seems to 
want to settle some score against music; all about music and its business come 
out looking foolish. It is not a nice or a fair book or an amusing book, but 
rather a sour one. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Book Review 
</P>
</TYPE>
