</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
853 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
A SEPARATE WAR; 
</P>
<P>
V FOR VICTOR BY MARK CHILDRESS (ALFRED A. KNOPF: $18.95; 289 PP.) 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Douglas Unger, Unger's most recent novel is The Turkey War. He is an 
associate professor with the Creative Writing Program at Syracuse University. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
It seems there are two kinds of novels about World War II. There are those 
books that attempt in fiction seriously to depict the war, its characters, its 
era, and to contribute to both literature and history. And there are other 
novels that merely use the war as a backdrop for a plotted story of intrigue 
and romance, exploiting what have too often become the "good" war's 
melodramatic ideologies of good and evil. 
</P>
<P>
Mark Childress' new book, "V for Victor," is just such a melodramatic story. 
World War II is used as a setting for an unlikely plot, the intent of which 
seems to be to spin an intricate mystery combined with a young man's struggles 
to come of age. 
</P>
<P>
The main character, Victor, is a boy of 16, living temporarily on a remote 
island in the mouth of the Magnolia River that spills into Alabama's Mobile 
Bay. He is there to accompany his grandmother, who has returned to the family's 
impoverished, backwater home to spend her last days. Victor's older brother, 
Joseph, is off at the front and considered by all to be a hero, overshadowing 
Victor's sense of himself. Perhaps because of this, and the isolation of the 
island and his grandmother's illness, Victor is filled with a strange 
combination of longing for the action of the war and a wish for his own death. 
"I wish we were both dead . . . ," he says to his grandmother as they listen to 
a heartbreaking, war-era song on the radio. "Who would care? Nobody." 
</P>
<P>
It is in this state of mind that Victor's improbable trajectory begins. He 
discovers a body washed ashore, and in so doing is bushwacked by another young 
boy, Butch, who guards illegal stills in the swamp. After an escape, Victor 
sets out across the bay in a small boat, looking to report the dead body to the 
law. He just happens to crash into a German submarine, sinks, and is 
miraculously saved by the local coast watcher, Roy Glass, who, as it turns out, 
is really an enemy agent disguised and passing himself off to everyone in this 
small-town Southern community as the coastal lawman. 
</P>
<P>
As though this weren't unbelievable enough, Victor is taken into the employ of 
a wealthy couple, Edgar Gilliam and his sinister, star actress wife, Constance 
Belair, as guide and boatboy on their luxurious yacht. There is a beautiful 
daughter involved, who provides this contrived story with a sexual interest. 
The backwoods still guard, Butch, somehow becomes Victor's friend and helper in 
unraveling the U-boat mystery. 
</P>
<P>
"V for Victor" is a story full of red herrings, double-agents, murder, unlikely 
confrontations and escapes. In one incident that not only asks of the reader a 
tough suspension of disbelief but an irritating battle against sheer 
incredulity, while pursuing the German U-boat in the luxury yacht, Victor and 
company watch a tanker sunk by torpedoes in Mobile Bay and, coincidentally, 
brother Joseph just happens to be pulled out of the burning wreckage. It turns 
out that he has deserted the Army overseas and has been working his way home on 
merchant ships. The crisis of youthful hero worship that Victor then must face 
is resolved in cliched B-movie fashion, with chase scenes, chance meetings, and 
a climactic fiery explosion. 
</P>
<P>
H. G. Wells once wrote a simple maxim about fiction -- "If nothing is 
believable, then nothing will be believed." That is almost the case with 
Childress' second novel. Anachronisms of language and historical 
impossibilities about the war abound through this story; so, too, does the plot 
resemble a very messily accomplished mystery about the Hardy Boys. 
</P>
<P>
But what is believable about "V for Victor," and a confirmation of the writing 
talent of young author Childress, is the occasional landscape or character 
description that does ring true: "The Magnolia River meanders for five miles 
down from its spring, widening, opening, mixing with the salty tide as it 
approaches Weeks Bay. This wide, shallow lake narrows down to a mouth. The 
lower jaw of this mouth was Willie's island -- a half mile of marsh grass, a 
long stretch of thickety woods, a high place of two or three acres well-shaded 
by live oaks, with Weeks Bay on one side and the big bay, Mobile, on the other. 
. . ." 
</P>
<P>
One senses that Childress, at least, knows his river vividly: "The boat stirred 
sideways from the dock. Imperceptibly it began gaining speed. The trees 
reflected the throb of its engines. Here the Magnolia was so narrow that Daniel 
could bush-hog both banks if he lowered his outriggers. His wake spread in a V, 
washing a flock of blackheaded ducks from their fallen log. . . ." 
</P>
<P>
This authenticity of landscape is the novel's strongest element. Also, the 
grandmother, Willie, who dies early in the story but lingers as a voice in 
Victor's mind, is a thoroughly interesting and credible character. It's 
unfortunate that Childress, in trying to exploit World War II for so much 
unbelievable action and melodrama, didn't concentrate more on what is truthful, 
penetrating, and honest about his landscape and people. But that would have 
meant a different kind of story set during the war era, and a book that would 
have made much more worthwhile reading. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Book Review 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA051489-0012 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 56614 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
May 14, 1989, Sunday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Book Review; Page 10; Book Review Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
1223 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
BLOODY SUNDAY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CHARLES CHAMPLIN 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Simon Brett, whose hard-drinking actor-sleuth Charles Paris is one of the joys 
of the mystery form, has begun a new series starring Melita Pargeter, a 
handsome widow whose late husband, a member of the criminal class, has left her 
plenty of money and a host of seedy but invaluable friends. 
</P>
<P>
In Mrs, Presumed Dead, Simon Brett (unequaled as an inventor of titles) has 
Mrs. Pargeter leasing a house in a spiffy suburban tract for the 
nouveau-mortgaged. The previous owner has left a false forwarding address and 
Pargeter correctly senses foul deeds. Her researches -- and Brett's dissection 
of the neighborhood and its upwardly striving residents -- make for very 
enjoyable reading. 
</P>
<P>
Santa Barbara's Sue Grafton has worked her way through Alibi, Burglar, Corpse, 
Deadbeat and Evidence and, with 'F' Is for Fugitive, shows no sign of faltering 
or flagging. Her Kinsey Millhone, one of the principal ladies in the private 
investigator line, is this time holed up in a California coast town that could 
be, let's say, Pismo Beach. 
</P>
<P>
A man, then a teen-ager, convicted of strangling his pregnant girlfriend, 
escaped from prison and now has been recaptured after 17 years of a blameless 
life under another name. Millhone has to rake through the dead past to see if 
he was, in fact, guilty as charged. 
</P>
<P>
After all those years there are enough lively suspects to fill a jail and 
enough evil to make "Peyton Place" seem like a retirement home for the serenely 
virtuous. Millhone's own life is finally at high risk. She is a wonderful 
character, tough but not brutish, resourceful and sensitive, a fit knight to 
walk those mean streets with her male predecessors, and high time. 
</P>
<P>
Robert B. Parker's Spenser books have seemed slighter right along, the paddings 
of sex and food ever more evident. But his new one, Playmates, while the 
pausings for play and nourishment are still overabundant, has an unusually 
interesting and affecting main thrust. 
</P>
<P>
A star college basketballer, who is black, has been shaving points and the 
scandal could imperil the team's shot at an NCAA title. Parker is here having 
his say about college athletics as the tail that wags the academic dog. He is 
also showing his wrath at the corrupting of the athletes themselves. There are 
corrosive portraits of a faculty choosing to ignore (and conceal) the fact that 
the star is functionally illiterate. 
</P>
<P>
The gamblers are of course murderously resentful of Spenser's interference, 
although murder when it happens is almost a side issue. Spenser, as is his 
admirable custom, is risking his own image in hope of reclaiming a single, 
sullen life, redirecting an athlete whose physical skills, seemingly a way out 
of poverty, have only made him a pawn in other people's nasty games. 
"Playmates" is one of Parker's best in some time. 
</P>
<P>
It's not surprising to learn that Bernard Schopen has completed a critical 
study of Ross Macdonald's work. Schopen's own first mystery, The Big Silence, 
is very strongly in the Macdonald tradition. 
</P>
<P>
There is, to begin with, a knowing and affectionate celebration of a particular 
turf. In Schopen's case it is the Nevada desert (he studied in Reno but now 
lives in New Hampshire). More important, there are the roots of present murder 
which go deep into an incredibly entangled past of hidden and concealed 
identities and undisclosed crimes. 
</P>
<P>
Schopen's hero is a lawyer-investigator named Jack Ross, who has about had it 
with death and betrayal, and is teetering at the brink of total emotional 
collapse. But when a young hooker asks him to find her grandfather, missing 
these 40 years, and Ross' old friend, an Indian, asks him to help her, what can 
he do? The writing occasionally strains too hard for poetic and rhetorical 
effects, trying for but missing Macdonald's heightened feeling for but careful 
control of language. The impersonations, the cross-breedings, the blood and 
marital ties, are almost too confusing, even compared with the messes Lew 
Archer ran into. But the action is vigorous and well-described, the Reno 
environs (even including the Mustang Ranch) excellently evoked, and Schopen and 
Ross are names to watch for henceforth. 
</P>
<P>
The prolific Lawrence Sanders ("The Anderson Tapes" and "Timothy's Game" most 
recently) has built Capital Crimes around a fascinating central figure. He is a 
vodka-swilling, womanizing faith healer who calls himself Brother Kristos and 
operates out of a decrepit tobacco barn in Virginia, with a pair of sluttish 
women as his handmaidens. 
</P>
<P>
The fascination is that he is not a fake; the cures appear to work, 
inexplicably, and word of him gets to the White House, where the President -- 
Abner Hawkins by name -- has a hemophiliac son, whom Kristos helps. 
</P>
<P>
Kristos quickly becomes a political issue, living in Washington, frequenting 
the White House, advising on social policy, becoming the inadvertent catalyst 
in a conspiracy. Sanders, infusing his thriller with an unusual amount of 
ambiguity, has written a suspenseful story that doubles as an essay on the 
corruptions of power, including power that may be unearthly. 
</P>
<P>
In the way of most softcover originals, Gerald Laurence's One Bang-Up Job, is a 
rocketingly fast, sleek-surfaced, larger-than-anything thriller. It confirms 
that the lessons of eventful pacing that made the pulp magazines as good as 
they were in their heyday have been noted and retained. 
</P>
<P>
Laurence's caper is a master-planned robbery of everything in San Francisco 
simultaneously, with a resulting haul of $30 million in cash, which seems 
modest enough, every till in the city having been raked clear, although 
naturally mastermind Daniel Langer had expenses. 
</P>
<P>
The author enlivens his fable with alternating first-person narratives, the 
pursuer reciting one chapter, the pursued the next. The chase leads to the 
jungles of South America, and Things Happen. Do they ever. In the end, of 
course, crime does not pay, but getting to this ancient wisdom is all the fun. 
</P>
<P>
While My Pretty One Sleeps is the seventh and latest by Mary Higgins Clark (15 
million copies in print, her publisher says). This one begins with the macabre 
disposal of the body of a murdered gossip columnist who had a flair for 
exposes. 
</P>
<P>
The rest of the book charts the slow realization by the columnist's friends 
(few) and acquaintances (many) that she is not simply unaccountably away, but 
dead. The central worrier is a boutique owner whose father, conveniently, is a 
former police commissioner. The suspects include a weak and sponging nephew, an 
ex-husband and his shrewish wife and some garment trade executives about whom 
she knew too much. 
</P>
<P>
The denouement is exciting if not overly surprising, and the book, for which a 
high competence is the accurate accolade, is hammock fare, if anyone still has 
hammocks. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
MRS, PRESUMED DEAD 
</P>
<P>
by Simon Brett 
</P>
<P>
(Scribner's: $16.95; 248 pp.) 
</P>
<P>
'F' IS FOR FUGITIVE 
</P>
<P>
by Sue Grafton 
</P>
<P>
(Henry Holt: $15.95; 261 pp.) 
</P>
<P>
PLAYMATES 
</P>
<P>
by Robert B. Parker 
</P>
<P>
(G.P. Putnam's Sons: 
</P>
<P>
$17.95; 224 pp.) 
</P>
<P>
THE BIG SILENCE 
</P>
<P>
by Bernard Schopen 
</P>
<P>
(Mysterious Press: 
</P>
<P>
$16.95; 263 pp.) 
</P>
<P>
CAPITAL CRIMES 
</P>
<P>
by Lawrence Sanders 
</P>
<P>
(G.W. Putnam's Sons: 
</P>
<P>
$19.95; 381 pp.) 
</P>
<P>
ONE BANG-UP JOB 
</P>
<P>
by Gerald Lawrence 
</P>
<P>
(Berkley: $3.95, 
</P>
<P>
paper; 298 pp.) 
</P>
<P>
WHILE MY PRETTY 
</P>
<P>
ONE SLEEPS 
</P>
<P>
by Mary Higgins Clark 
</P>
<P>
(Simon &amp; Schuster: 
</P>
<P>
$19.95; 318 pp.) 
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Simon Brett JERRY BAUER; Photo, Sue Grafton 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
<TYPE>
