<HEADLINE>
<P>
SEARCH FOR A FIRST 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
While I agree with Boyd that "it's high time someone set the record straight on 
when the first TV movie was made," his assignation of that honor to NBC's "The 
Pied Piper of Hamelin" is seriously misplaced. 
</P>
<P>
During the first season of "Playhouse 90" on CBS (1956-57), no fewer than 10 of 
this renowned live drama show's 39 presentations were feature-length films 
produced especially for television. (The first was "The Country Husband," based 
on a John Cheever story, which aired on Nov. 1, 1956.) It seems to me that 
these qualify as "made-for-TV movies" by any but the most hair-splitting 
definition. 
</P>
<P>
Even these had at least one antecedent, however: a 72-minute film called "Black 
Forest," starring Peggy Ann Garner and Akim Tamiroff, made in Germany by an 
American company, for distribution to independent stations. Variety reviewed 
this production on Feb. 3, 1954, noting that "the 'expressly-for-TV' angle 
lends itself strongly to prestige-type ballyhoo on the part of station and 
sponsor, and its effect on the public is not to be minimized." 
</P>
<P>
HOWARD H. PROUTY 
</P>
<P>
Van Nuys 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Letter to the Editor 
</P>
