<HEADLINE>
<P>
VIEWPOINTS; 
</P>
<P>
IS CONSUMERISM A REBEL CAUSE?; 
</P>
<P>
PUBLIC OPINION WATCHERS SEE A MOVEMENT BUT AREN'T SURE IT CAN BE CALLED A 
REVOLT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
On several fronts, consumerism appears to be on the rise. Consumers have 
protested everything from the handling of the Exxon Valdez oil spill to the 
rise of "reality-based" television to the use of pesticides. Earlier this 
month, another blow was struck for consumerism when the U.S. Supreme Court 
upheld most of California's Proposition 103 initiative to tighten regulation of 
the insurance industry. Does all of this signal the start of a powerful and 
widespread consumer revolt? What's influencing the changing mood of consumers, 
and what are its implications? Times researcher Melanie Pickett raised these 
questions with various people who keep a close eye on public opinion, and 
excerpts of their comments follow. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
Andrew Kohut, president of the Gallup Organization: 
</P>
<P>
"The most important thing to recognize is that a Populist attitude toward 
American business is a fundamental American value. Americans consistently 
believe that companies have profits that are way too large, and feel that large 
companies have too much power. And when they see incidents such as Valdez, or 
they read about pesticide pollution or what have you, it strikes a chord that 
resonates with the public. They are situations that tap into people's general 
distrust of business. Whether consumerism will become once again a very 
focused, crystallized movement in the way it was in the early '70s, I don't 
know. I don't have any evidence of that. . . . 
</P>
<P>
"One of the important values that animates public opinion is the suspicion of 
business. . . . What our studies show is that the feeling is greater among 
women than it is among men, that women tend to be consumerist to a far greater 
degree than men, and that older people are much more suspicious of the motives 
and power of American business than younger people. So if you're going to find 
a rebirth of consumerism, it is probably not going to be among young people. 
It's going to be among middle-aged and older people, and it's probably going to 
be among women." 
</P>
<P>
Paul Ambrosino, a San Francisco political consultant: 
</P>
<P>
"Just watching debate, listening to candidates and looking at referendums, I 
think it would be an overstatement to suggest that a consumer revolt is out 
there in the making. You may get some initial reactions, such as an AK-47 ban, 
that will dominate public policy as a dramatic event takes place as in 
Stockton. And who knows if you'll see some sort of similar type initiative as a 
result of the (Exxon Valdez oil spill) or an incident like that. 
</P>
<P>
"I think what's going on in places like California is that some of the 
traditional (consumer issues) that have been debated for a long, long time 
without being resolved are going to end up more and more on the ballot. (People 
are) figuring out that what they can't get in the legislature, they can put 
before consumers and voters through initiatives. The successful passage of the 
insurance proposition is likely to whet the appetite of activists to go after 
other items they have not been able to achieve in the legislative process. I'm 
not sure I think that's a consumer revolt, I think it's the interests taking 
the battleground to a different arena. 
</P>
<P>
"What I think you see in the citizens out there is that they are receptive to 
voting in favor of those types of measures. . . . Until consumers sense they 
lose by passing one of these, you can always find people interested in giving 
themselves a break at the expense of a large institution or company." 
</P>
<P>
Craig Gordon, director of Grassroots Research, which tracks new products and 
trends: 
</P>
<P>
"The consumer is getting more active. I don't know if it's a revolt yet. . . . 
Manufacturers have become real sensitive to it. Almost every consumer product 
now has an "800" complaint line. A lot of manufacturers have discovered they'd 
rather have the person vent the frustration at them instead of going to other 
avenues, whether it's government or boycotting the product or whatever. There's 
a lot more choices and a lot less brand loyalty than there was before. . . . I 
think businesses are becoming more aware of how important it is to get the 
consumer in the decision-making process." 
</P>
<P>
Dave Stewart, marketing professor at the USC Graduate School of Business: 
</P>
<P>
"If you look at the whole history of the consumer movement in the U.S., it has 
tended to go in cycles. And I think we've come through a cycle where there has 
been a de-emphasis on regulation, a de-emphasis on protecting the consumer. 
Consumers have been more dormant. 
</P>
<P>
"We are probably now moving into another up cycle because of a host of things 
that have come to the fore: concerns about the oil spill, concerns about 
general increases in the price of oil, concerns about pesticides, we could go 
on and on. These things are now beginning to receive more play in the press, 
they receive a receptive ear. In addition, the Bush Administration seems to be 
more open to regulation so that the Federal Trade Commission, among others, has 
shown evidence of beginning to become more active. They've been pushed somewhat 
as well by more activist groups of state attorneys general. I think it's fair 
to say we're seeing an upsurge. How far it will go I think remains to be seen. 
</P>
<P>
"What you'll begin to see -- (and) already are beginning to see -- are efforts 
on the part of industry to tell its story so that the people have more 
information, more correct information. You'll see companies running more 
campaigns that document what they're doing to clean up the environment. And 
there are a number of companies which are well known already for that kind of 
campaign -- Weyerhaeuser has for years talked about the number of trees it 
plants as opposed to the number they chop down. You'll hear more of that so 
that business gets across the idea that there is another side to the story, 
that they do try to behave responsibly." 
</P>
<P>
Michael Cunningham, associate professor of psychology at the University of 
Louisville: 
</P>
<P>
"Look at demographics -- that's the first issue. One of the facts of political 
life is that the baby boom generation that was always somewhat cynical toward 
institutions is becoming more politically potent. The second aspect is that the 
education level in America, although incredibly uneven in its distribution, is 
gradually creeping upward. There are more college-educated people who tend to 
be skeptical of what is offered to them. 
</P>
<P>
"Those two highly correlated demographic facts mean there are opportunities for 
people to be engaged in political activities on those things that touch their 
lives. 
</P>
<P>
"Now, regulation gets to be a very tricky issue. One of the interesting facts 
is those people who are cynical about business are also cynical about 
government. One fragment goes for greater regulation and that will be 
continuing to increase. But another group probably has two types in its numbers 
-- one are the Reagan 'true believers' who believe in deregulation and don't 
believe in government intrusion, and a second group that is cynical about 
government and prefers to handle things on the local level. Some people will 
say, for example, 'Let's regulate apples. Make sure there's no Alar.' The other 
group will say, 'Well, let's just buy organic and let's not waste our time 
trying to move through Congress a series of regulations.' 
</P>
<P>
"A consumer movement is going to, I suspect, be a very fragmented thing. 
Different types of industries will encounter different types of pressure groups 
because behind the consumer movement are a series of very different kinds of 
people with very different kinds of agendas." 
</P>
<P>
Gary Flint, director of Consumer Protection Agency, a nonprofit foundation: 
</P>
<P>
"California has probably the best consumer protection laws in the country. What 
concerns a lot of consumers is not that we have inadequate laws, it's just that 
it's not possible to enforce every law in every case. 
</P>
<P>
"In general, if you have more regulation than we have now, it could hurt the 
consumer. . . . We have to retrain our thought to be more goal oriented than 
legislation oriented. The government became too big, in many ways, in the '60s, 
which actually hurt the consumers. It raised taxes and increased the size of 
government. . . . If you were to ask people across the country what they think 
about consumerism today as opposed to the way it was several years ago, I think 
they'd say there is somewhat of a voter revolt afoot." 
</P>
<P>
Ed Zwick, co-producer of the television show "thirtysomething": 
</P>
<P>
"Deregulation in a lot of areas isn't immediately perceived but I think it 
clearly is now beginning to be, and its implications for consumer issues are 
pretty obvious. The real interesting question over the next number of years 
will be whether what now seems to be a grass-roots sense of indignation will 
translate into any real shift in policy politically. Has consumerism been 
enough of an issue to sway electoral politics and legislation? Not in recent 
memory. . . . Will it become more important? I feel certain candidates (are) 
beginning to position themselves as the beneficiaries of what they perceive to 
be a movement." 
</P>
</TEXT>
<CORRECTION-DATE>
<P>
May 16, 1989, Tuesday, Home Edition 
</P>
</CORRECTION-DATE>
<CORRECTION>
<P>
FOR THE RECORD 
</P>
<P>
The California Supreme Court upheld most of Proposition 103, the state's 
insurance regulation initiative. A column in Sunday's business section 
inaccurately stated that the U.S. Supreme Court made the ruling. 
</P>
</CORRECTION>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Drawing, RICHARD DOWNS / for The Times 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
