<HEADLINE>
<P>
TRIBUTE TO A SLAIN ATHLETE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The 2,000 students of John Glenn High School in Norwalk filled the school's 
quad Thursday for an emotional memorial service for Juan Enriquez, 18, a senior 
football and wrestling star who was killed Tuesday in a drive-by shooting near 
his south Norwalk home. Students carried red, white and blue balloons and the 
football players wore their red jerseys. 
</P>
<P>
"Only a few days ago he was playing out here with everyone who was close to 
him," Principal Elias Galvan said, speaking at a podium decorated with 
Enriquez's letterman's jacket. "He always had a smile and friends around him. 
He always had a sense of pride and dignity. He did things to improve the image 
of John Glenn High School." 
</P>
<P>
Anger was expressed at gang activity. 
</P>
<P>
Mayor Grace Napolitano said: "I'm speechless. It can't happen to us, but it can 
and it did. We have had enough, guys, enough of the violence, enough of the 
drugs. All of you have a responsibility to this (Enriquez) family, to yourself 
and to the community to cure what the heck is going on in this community. Until 
you wake up and start making a difference, who's going to be next?" 
</P>
<P>
Ernie Gutierrez, a football player, directed his comments at any gang members 
who might have been in the audience: "Chaka wasn't even in a gang . . . what do 
you think the chances are for you?" Football Coach Willie Norman announced that 
Enriquez's football jersey, No. 77, would be retired. The jersey he wore last 
season was given to his mother, Theresa Enriquez, who sat on the stage with her 
family and Caprice Fimbres, who had been Enriquez's girlfriend. 
</P>
<P>
Tearful students expressed their feelings for Enriquez by sharing their 
memories of him and by reading poems they had written. 
</P>
<P>
Students also placed wreaths on the sidewalk at Horst Avenue and Algardi Street 
where Enriquez was gunned down. Football and wrestling jerseys with memorial 
messages written on them were left at the scene. Students also scribbled 
messages on the pavement. 
</P>
<P>
Members of Enriquez's family, including his mother, also visited the student 
memorial. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Theresa Enriquez cries on sidewalk where her son, Juan, was killed. 
Friends' messages are written on pavement. ; Photo, Hand-written notes of love 
and remembrance cover shirt hanging on fence at Norwalk shooting scene. ; 
Photo, Students at John Glenn High School comfort one another during memorial 
service for Juan Enriquez. EUGENE TANNER / Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
