<HEADLINE>
<P>
HEALTH CLINIC RHETORIC 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
On Tuesday, the San Diego city school board will face a tough decision: whether 
to give conceptual approval for a health clinic to serve 8,000 students at 
several East San Diego schools. 
</P>
<P>
The decision will not be tough for the usual financial reasons. The clinic's 
operating costs would come primarily from private foundations. The school 
district's contribution would mostly be in administrative services and donated 
space. 
</P>
<P>
What makes the decision tough is the opposition of a vocal minority, led by the 
Catholic bishop, who, in a pastoral letter called the health centers "sex 
clinics" in disguise that will promote free sex, contraception, masturbation 
and abortion. 
</P>
<P>
Such rhetoric is absurd. First of all, the clinic will not provide abortion 
referrals or information. Second, if it provides birth-control information and 
devices -- and it should -- that is not synonymous with promoting sexual 
activity. It only recognizes that many teen-agers are sexually active whether 
or not their parents want them to be. 
</P>
<P>
Third, all services will require parental permission. The notion that state law 
would overrule that requirement has not proven true at clinics elsewhere in 
California, and school district officials say opponents are misinterpreting the 
law. 
</P>
<P>
What school board members need to keep uppermost in their minds is that the 
medical and mental-health services the clinic would provide are sorely needed. 
The religious beliefs of a minority should not be able to deny those services 
to the majority who support them. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Editorial 
</P>
