<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE MARKETING: A SUMMER CRUSADE FOR BAT DOLLARS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By STACY JENEL SMITH 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Holy merchandising dollars, Batman! 
</P>
<P>
When the Caped Crusader swoops into movie theaters this summer, he won't be 
empty-handed. He'll be hauling along a cargo of products mighty enough to 
satisfy the ego of any superhero. 
</P>
<P>
In fact, despite competition from such notables as Indiana Jones, the 
Ghostbusters, and Peter Pan, Batman is already being called the sure -- and 
easy -- victor in this summer's movie merchandising sweepstakes by toy industry 
analysts, retail store buyers and memorabilia dealers. 
</P>
<P>
The Batman product blowout runs the gamut, from everyday movie tie-ins like 
posters, key chains and automobile sunshades to imaginative goodies including a 
$150 motorized ride-on Batmobile for kids. 
</P>
<P>
On their way to stores this summer are Batman Nintendo games, Batman walkie 
talkies, Batman shirts, robes, pajamas -- even Batman boxer shorts -- and 
Batman costumes ranging from $6 vinyl hooded capes to $200-plus Bat wear 
fashioned along the lines of Michael Keaton's film wardrobe. 
</P>
<P>
The New York-based Toy Biz company is putting out a Batman line that includes 
plastic replicas of the movie's rocket-launching Batwing aircraft ($15.25) and 
ultra high-tech Bat Cave ($17.95). 
</P>
<P>
And, of course, there's much more. 
</P>
<P>
In addition to the 24 companies who have deals with Warner Bros. to produce 
items in conjunction with the Batman movie, D.C. Comics has licensed 101 
companies in the United States and Canada to manufacture products in honor of 
the Caped Crusader's 50th birthday this year. 
</P>
<P>
It may well be that comic-book Batman, clad in his classic blue-and-gray gear, 
turns out to be the toughest competition for Batman, the all-in-black film 
star. Both Batmen, however, face some dynamic challengers, including: 
</P>
<P>
* Indiana Jones. With "Indiana Jones and the Last Crusade" set for a May 24 
opening, Indy is about to become quite a ubiquitous guy around supermarkets and 
convenience stores participating in the Pepsi company's summerlong "Indiana 
Jones" contest/promotion. Giveaways include a trip for two to Venice or Egypt, 
"adventure kits" (complete with khaki-colored Indy watches, soft drink coolers, 
visors, sweat bands and radios), adventurous Indy-style jackets and Stetson 
hats and movie posters. 
</P>
<P>
For those who would rather buy their Indy gear outright, some similar items 
will be available through retail stores. 
</P>
<P>
* Ghostbusters. Although "Ghostbusters II" movie tie-in items including fabric 
"Ghostbusters" costumes ($14.99) and vinyl "Slimer" duds ($5.99) are expected 
to appear in stores by summer's end, the real powerhouse "Ghostbusters" line is 
already on the shelves. Kenner's "The Real Ghostbusters" cartoon show tie-ins 
comprised an $80 million toy line in 1988. With some additional products, it's 
expected to grow to $100 million in 1989. 
</P>
<P>
* Peter Pan. Sears has an exclusive deal to sell "Peter Pan" products in 
conjunction with the re-release of the 1953 Disney classic. The company expects 
to have "Peter Pan" items including dolls and plush toys ($10-$20) and 
children's apparel ($5.33-$20) in stores by July 1. 
</P>
<P>
* Babar. In terms of movie merchandise, the dark horse of the summer may turn 
out to be an elephant. "Babar is a 56-year-old classic character who has never 
really been exploited, until now," notes Stanford Blum, executive vice 
president of the Toronto-based Nelvana Entertainment. Nelvana ("The Care 
Bears") plans to open its animated "Babar: The Movie" in 800 theaters 
nationwide July 28. The company also has a commitment for 65 episodes of HBO's 
twice-a-week "Babar" series, which debuted April 1. 
</P>
<P>
Nelvana has licensed some 40 U.S. manufacturers and 60 foreign companies to 
produce a truly elephantine quantity of Babar toys and other goods. Since it 
views Babar as "a yuppie property," says Blum, the firm began its product 
launch at department stores on the level of Bloomingdale's and Neiman Marcus, 
pushing plush toys (priced at up to a very plush $500), lead crystal, jewelry, 
linen and other upscale items. 
</P>
<P>
This summer, Babar will lumber into more common territory with less pricey 
</P>
<P>
merchandise as well as personal appearances at shopping centers and malls 
across the country. "We have 20 Babar costumes and they're all booked for the 
summer," reports Blum. 
</P>
<P>
And if that's not enough to place Babar in the collective consciousness of Los 
Angeles residents, Nelvana has also orchestrated a June 28 event at the L.A. 
Zoo in which a newly "adopted" elephant will be named King Babar. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Drawing, The Batmobile toy. ; Photo, Babar the elephant. 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
<SUBJECT>
<P>
MOTION PICTURES; MARKETING; PRODUCTS; SUMMER; 1989 
</P>
</SUBJECT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA051489-0132 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 56914 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
May 14, 1989, Sunday, Home Edition 
</P>
