<HEADLINE>
<P>
CITYLINES: MORE TO WRIGHT MYTH 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Sam Hall Kaplan 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The interest in all things Frank Lloyd Wright continues. The latest book on who 
many consider America's greatest architect of the ages is "Frank Lloyd Wright: 
The Crowning Decade, 1949-1959, Selected, and With a Commentary, by Bruce 
Brooks Pfeiffer" (The Press at Cal State, Fresno: $22.95 hardback, $13.95 
paperback.) 
</P>
<P>
The thin book of large type and a selection of personal photographs focuses on 
the last 10 years of the architect's tumultuous life. Offered are views of 
Wright by the public through a selection of articles; Wright's own reflections; 
his wife's, drawn from her own personal papers; his daughter's, through 
interviews, and those of his apprentices. 
</P>
<P>
Although when his widow, Olgivanna, is quoted as saying shortly before her 
death, "I ruled him, but I ruled him with love," it is perhaps more than we 
want to know. Nevertheless, the volume adds to the myth that was Wright, and is 
sure to be of interest to his faithful followers. Sam Hall Kaplan 
</P>
</TEXT>
