<HEADLINE>
<P>
TEACHERS DESCRIBE A YOUNG MAN WHO ALWAYS KNEW WHO HE WAS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
As former teachers of Julian Cummings, we read with great pleasure and pride 
your account (May 3) of his achievements at UC Berkeley. Even as a junior high 
school student, Julian knew who he was and what he wanted in a remarkably 
mature sense, so all that he has accomplished in the years after he left us 
comes as little surprise. 
</P>
<P>
Ironically, the wording of the article's title, "Honors Graduate Had an Uphill 
Fight," revived one of our fondest memories of Julian. As an eighth-grader 
participating in a study trip to Yosemite, Julian wanted to have the same 
experiences as anyone else visiting the park. To realize this desire, he 
selected many activities that would challenge his physical abilities, one of 
which was a hike to the top of Yosemite Falls. Although we all admired his 
determination, we doubted such an arduous undertaking fell within the range of 
his ability. 
</P>
<P>
As usual, however, Julian knew himself better than we did. When he and his 
father finally returned from their successful climb -- long after everyone else 
had come back to camp and well past the time we had begun to become concerned 
-- we were privileged to share a triumph with him and his parents that is 
unique in all our years of Yosemite experiences. 
</P>
<P>
As a result, we've known all along that "uphill battles" are challenges that 
Julian meets with purpose and effectiveness. We congratulate him on his 
outstanding achievements and wish him every happiness and success in the 
future. Julian Cummings will always have a special place in our teaching 
memories. 
</P>
<P>
JOY DE GRUCCIO 
</P>
<P>
JAY DU VAL 
</P>
<P>
ROY COLLIER 
</P>
<P>
MARY COLLIER 
</P>
<P>
Huntington Beach 
</P>
</TEXT>
