<HEADLINE>
<P>
IRVINE'S RIGHTS LAW AND THE ATTEMPT TO AMEND IT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
After reading "A Matter of Values, Political Semantics" (May 4) I wonder: What 
other "behaviors" disturb Scott Peotter's "traditional values" system? And I 
have pondered what group, included in the Irvine human rights ordinance, will 
be the next target of his coalition on account of their "behavior." 
</P>
<P>
Peotter tells us that his set of values came from the "Founding Fathers"; 
however, he fails to realize they were a great group of activists -- perhaps 
even radicals -- who, in their own time, overthrew a government! And while I 
don't know if any were gay, some were quite noteworthy for their womanizing and 
boozing. 
</P>
<P>
Throughout history, a few so-called traditionists have excluded many with their 
one-dimensional view of what society should be. Now that the initiative to 
discriminate against sexual orientation will appear on the November ballot, I 
feel certain that a majority of the people of Irvine will use three-dimensional 
vision and vote it down. 
</P>
<P>
MARTHA BELL 
</P>
<P>
Seal Beach 
</P>
</TEXT>
