<HEADLINE>
<P>
SOUTHERN SECTION 3-A SWIMMING CHAMPIONSHIPS; 
</P>
<P>
LOS ALAMITOS GIRLS WIN SECOND TITLE IN A ROW 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CHRIS FOSTER, Times Staff Writer 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
At the start of the season, Los Alamitos High School girls' swim Coach Debbie 
Flemming thought her team was good enough to repeat as 3-A champions. 
</P>
<P>
She was right. 
</P>
<P>
The Griffins made fast work of the competition Saturday in the finals at 
Belmont Plaza pool. By the time the first individual event was over, there was 
little doubt who was in charge. 
</P>
<P>
Los Alamitos not only had the winner in the 200-yard freestyle, it had the 
third- and fourth-place finishers as well. 
</P>
<P>
Stacy St. Martin won the event with a time of 1 minute 51.27 seconds. Marci 
Herron was third (1:54.78) and Kim Rubino fourth (1:56.12). 
</P>
<P>
Only Natalie Norberg of San Marino kept it from being a clean sweep, finishing 
second (1:52.24). 
</P>
<P>
With that kind of depth, the Griffins were unstoppable. They finished with 195 
points, well ahead of second-place El Dorado, which had 104. 
</P>
<P>
"We looked really strong in the preliminaries, so I didn't think anyone would 
challenge us," Flemming said. "And everybody, I mean everybody, swam their best 
times in the finals." 
</P>
<P>
Los Alamitos has always had a strong girls' swim team. The Griffins have won 
six consecutive Empire League championships. 
</P>
<P>
But, until last season, they had never won a Southern Section title. 
</P>
<P>
"It was getting old just winning league championships," Flemming said. "Our 
goal last season was to win the Southern Section title. We did, and we made our 
goal to repeat this year. I felt with the talent we had coming back, we should 
win it again." 
</P>
<P>
The Griffins lost only one swimmer from last year's team. They qualified 12 
swimmers for the finals as well as two relay teams. 
</P>
<P>
And, as Flemming said, everyone was at their best. 
</P>
<P>
Besides St. Martin's victory in the 200 freestyle, the Griffins received a 
first-place finish from Marci Herron. 
</P>
<P>
Herron won the 100 freestyle with a time of 53.11. Rubino was fifth in that 
event. 
</P>
<P>
Los Alamitos also won the 400 freestyle relay with time of 3:35.40. It was 
eight seconds faster than San Marino, which finished second in the event. 
</P>
<P>
The Griffins also received a strong performance from Nicole Williamson, who 
finished second in the 200 individual medley and 500 freestyle. 
</P>
<P>
Second was no disgrace as both those events were won by three-time Olympic 
gold-medalist Janet Evans. 
</P>
<P>
Evans set a national high school record in the 200 individual medley with a 
time of 1:59.96. She also just missed the record in the 500 freestyle with a 
time of 4:38.34. 
</P>
<P>
Despite being used to international competition, Evans, a senior, has found 
plenty of motivation on the high school level. 
</P>
<P>
"My coach has found ways to get me motivated," said Evans, who will attend 
Stanford next year. "Stuff like setting goals for times and trying to lap the 
other swimmers. It's helped me get ready for these meets." 
</P>
<P>
Williamson swam strong times in both events. She went 2:05.54 in the 200 
individual medley and 4:53.60 in the 500 freestyle. 
</P>
<P>
"I was really happy for Nicole and Janet," Flemming said. "They have been very 
good friends for a long time. Nicole will be back next year, so it will be hers 
to win." 
</P>
<P>
San Marino won the boys' meet for the second consecutive year. The Titans 
finished with 179 points. Damien was second with 132 and Santa Monica third 
with 98. 
</P>
<P>
Servite was the top Orange County team at the meet. The Friars scored 55 
points, good enough for 10th place. 
</P>
<P>
In the girls' competition, Deborah Kory of Rolling Hills broke the 3-A record 
in the 100 backstroke with a time of 1:05.87. The previous mark was 1:06.23, 
set by Shannon Breese of Thousand Oaks in 1984. 
</P>
<P>
With Evans swimming the opening leg, El Dorado's 200 medley relay team finished 
first with a time of 1:53.13. 
</P>
<P>
But the night, again, belonged to Los Alamitos. 
</P>
<P>
"Hey we have everyone returning next year," Flemming said. "This could be a 
dynasty." 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Game Story 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA051489-0228 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 57454 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
May 14, 1989, Sunday, Orange County Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Business; Part 4; Page 1; Column 3; Financial Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
1971 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
NATIONAL EDUCATION'S CHIEF TOP O.C. EARNER 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DAVID OLMOS, Times Staff Writer 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Jerome Cwiertnia earned a nifty $1.8 million in 1988 as president of National 
Education Corp., the nation's largest operator of vocational training schools. 
</P>
<P>
But Cwiertnia is living proof that money -- even lots of it -- doesn't always 
buy happiness in the executive suite. He quit his job with the Irvine firm last 
March to look for a position that would give him "more managerial 
responsibility." 
</P>
<P>
Cwiertnia's pay of $1.8 million made him the highest-paid manager among Orange 
County-based, publicly held corporations, according to The Times annual survey 
of executive compensation. Counting salary and stock options, Cwiertnia earned 
$360,000 more than his boss, H. David Bright, National Education's chairman. 
Bright was the county's second highest-paid executive, making nearly $1.5 
million last year. 
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, the pair of National Education executives earned far less than 
1987's top-earning corporate chiefs. James Conte, president of Community 
Psychiatric Centers in Laguna Hills, earned a whopping $8.5 million in 1987 -- 
with $7.6 million of that total coming from stock options. His boss, Community 
Psychiatric Chairman Robert L. Green, earned $6.8 million in 1987, including 
$6.3 million in stock options. 
</P>
<P>
Conte and Green do not appear on the 1988 list. The company declined to supply 
information on executive pay for the latest survey because it had not yet been 
disclosed in the company's proxy. 
</P>
<P>
The survey of about 2 dozen of Orange County's largest publicly traded 
companies, conducted by Mercer Meidinger Hansen for The Times, showed that pay 
for the county's top 10 executives averaged $998,000 in 1988, down from $2.4 
million in 1987. The large difference primarily reflects a big decline in 
profits taken by executives exercising stock options. 
</P>
<P>
The Top 25 list was dominated by the county's largest companies: National 
Education and home builder J.M. Peters each claimed four of the top-paid 
executives; Bergen Brunswig, a pharmaceutical distributor, placed three 
executives on the list, and five companies claimed two each. 
</P>
<P>
No female executives made the Top 25 list. 
</P>
<P>
Despite Orange County's reputation as a high-technology center, Western Digital 
Chairman Roger W. Johnson was the only high-tech executive to place in the top 
25. 
</P>
<P>
Johnson earned $565,578 in 1988, placing 12th on the list. But Western 
Digital's proxy also listed nearly $1.8 million in stock options. In Johnson's 
case, the stock-option earnings are not included in the compensation totals 
because it was believed that the options were paid out over a 3-year period 
ending in September, 1988. Western Digital would not say when the payments were 
made. 
</P>
<P>
Many top managers enjoyed big gains in 1987 by selling those options before the 
October, 1987, stock market crash. Stock prices were depressed throughout much 
of 1988, reducing the incentive for executives to trade their options for cash. 
</P>
<P>
While 1988 was not a big year for stock profits, National Education's Cwiertnia 
gained the top spot by exercising stock options worth $1.1 million. 
</P>
<P>
Stock options are a commonly used method of motivating and rewarding corporate 
executives. Typically, a stock-option program gives an employee the right to 
periodically purchase the company's shares at a fixed price -- at or below the 
market price -- for a certain number of years. 
</P>
<P>
If the stock's market price rises above the option price, the option may be 
exercised. The executive's profit is the difference between the option price 
and the market price. 
</P>
<P>
Compensation specialists say that stock options, while used widely at 
corporations nationwide, are becoming less attractive as a form of executive 
compensation for the smaller, fast-growing companies that are common in Orange 
County. 
</P>
<P>
"If an emerging company goes public and has widely dispersed stock options, 
then the higher the stock goes the more the company pays out in compensation," 
said David Thomsen, managing director of the Economic Research Institute in 
Newport Beach. "In some extreme cases, the stock price has gone so high that it 
has wiped out a firm's earnings per share." 
</P>
<P>
Thomsen said some Orange County companies are turning to 
alternative-compensation programs such as deferred or supplemental-compensation 
plans, which involve tax-free, interest-bearing accounts that the company 
typically contributes to. These programs are less risky than stock options, 
which often depend entirely on a company's stock performance. 
</P>
<P>
At companies where executives' pay was tied to the firm's performance, 
individuals reaped handsome rewards as profits soared. 
</P>
<P>
J.M. Peters Co., a Newport Beach home builder, enjoyed a strong 1988 thanks to 
the soaring county housing market. 
</P>
<P>
Company Chairman James M. Peters likes to reward people "not only by salary, 
but also with an incentive to perform," said Brian Teriot, a company spokesman. 
He said executives' salaries are often tied to the company's earnings or the 
number of house closings. 
</P>
<P>
Several J.M. Peters executives made out handsomely in 1988. 
</P>
<P>
Those executives included: J. Karl Kruetzer, president of the company's San 
Diego division, $531,804; Frank E. Fullerton, vice president, $512,550; Robert 
J. Trapp, vice president, $509,089, and Richard D. Bradshaw, vice president, 
$479,897. 
</P>
<P>
The two co-founders of Newport Beach-based Downey Savings &amp; Loan Assn. were 
generously rewarded. Company President Maurice L. McAlister made more than $1.1 
million in 1988, while Chief Executive Officer Gerald H. McQuarrie earned 
$820,947. 
</P>
<P>
Downey, one of the county's most profitable thrifts, had earnings of $29 
million on revenue of $330.8 million in 1988. 
</P>
<P>
McAlister and McQuarrie, neither of whom made 1987's list of highest-paid 
executives, made the 1988 list because of large bonuses. McAlister received a 
$750,000 bonus, McQuarrie a $500,000 bonus. 
</P>
<P>
"The board voted to give us the bonuses because we had excellent earnings for 
several years," McQuarrie said. "The two of us started the company (in 1957) 
and took no salaries for the first 3 or 4 years, and then took only $800 a 
month for about 10 years. 
</P>
<P>
"This was our first bonus in 30 years," he added. "And I'm not going to give it 
back to them." 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY'S HIGHEST-PAID EXECUTIVES 
</P>
<P>
Executives at publicly held Orange County companies ranked by total 
compensation reported for the most recent fiscal year. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
O.C. Rank: 1 
</P>
<P>
Name (State Rank): J.W. Cwiertnia (26) 
</P>
<P>
Company: National Education Corp 
</P>
<P>
Title: President 
</P>
<P>
** Golden Par., Emp. Agree.: Yes, Yes 
</P>
<P>
1988 Cash: $695,251 
</P>
<P>
1988 Long Term: $1,138,244 
</P>
<P>
1988 Total: $1,833,495 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
